On 04-10-2012 17:32, Youssef Eldakar wrote:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On Tue, Oct 2, 2012 at 10:18 PM, Noah Levitt &lt;nlevitt@... 
&gt; &lt;mailto:nlevitt@...&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;     Hello IIPC and heritrix communities,
&gt;
&gt;     I recently pushed code implementing url-agnostic identical content
&gt;     payload digest deduplication to the heritrix source code
&gt;     repository (see
&gt;     https://webarchive.jira.com/browse/HER-2022). The idea is that if two
&gt;     urls have the same content, that content need only be archived once.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Good work, Noah.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;     Here is an example warc record for a deduplicated payload, as
&gt;     currently
&gt;     written:
&gt;
&gt;     WARC/1.0
&gt;     WARC-Type: revisit
&gt;     WARC-Target-URI: http://archive-it.org/image/account/logo/643
&gt;     WARC-Date: 2012-09-14T00:23:34Z
&gt;     WARC-Payload-Digest: sha1:RUQRLRH2XOX6DQWUUVFXHO25OBQBWUJG
&gt;     WARC-IP-Address: 207.241.235.232
&gt;     WARC-Profile:
&gt;     http://netpreserve.org/warc/1.0/revisit/identical-payload-digest
&gt;     WARC-Truncated: length
&gt;     WARC-Refers-To: &lt;urn:uuid:38d12614-19dc-4bb0-9b6c-f98ebcf7cc52&gt;
&gt;     WARC-Refers-To-Target-URI:
&gt;     http://archive-it.org/image/featured-organizations/643/tn
&gt;     WARC-Refers-To-Date: 2012-09-13T23:06:21Z
&gt;     WARC-Refers-To-Filename:
&gt;     WEB-20120913230526198-00000-32360~localhost.archive.org
&gt;     &lt;http://localhost.archive.org&gt;~6440.warc.gz
&gt;     WARC-Refers-To-File-Offset: 2002421
&gt;     WARC-Record-ID: &lt;urn:uuid:306e9752-9b8c-49dd-bbd2-de06feace703&gt;
&gt;     Content-Type: application/http; msgtype=response
&gt;     Content-Length: 149
&gt;
&gt;     HTTP/1.1 200 OK
&gt;     Date: Fri, 14 Sep 2012 00:23:34 GMT
&gt;     Server: Apache-Coyote/1.1
&gt;     Content-Type: image/png
&gt;     Content-Length: 7904
&gt;     Connection: close
&gt;
&gt;     These records are very similar to old url-specific revisit
&gt;     records, but
&gt;     with the addition of the WARC-Refers-To* group of fields.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Target-URI, Date, File-Offset, and Filename, right, those are the 4 
&gt; variables one needs to identify the original copy. I am thinking, In 
&gt; subsequent revisit records, should this set of Refers-To-* fields 
&gt; point to the previous revisit or to the actual original copy? I think 
&gt; I would vote for the latter to avoid possibly long traversals when 
&gt; resolving revisit records.

In case of repackaging of WARC files the WARC-Refers-To-Filename and 
WARC-Refers-To-Offset will be rendered invalid.
As I understand the example (WARC-Refers-To-Target-URI, 
WARC-Refers-To-Date, WARC-Refers-To-Filename, 
WARC-Refers-To-File-Offset) are just copies of information which is 
pointed to by the WARC-Refers-To URI?

Why not stick with WARC-Refers-To and a new profile URI. Leaving the 
other information to external indexing which is required anyway for 
large collections of WARC files.

&gt;
&gt;     In addition, the warc spec seems to specify that that WARC-Profile
&gt;     http://netpreserve.org/warc/1.0/revisit/identical-payload-digest
&gt;     should
&gt;     only be used for recrawls of the same url. It &quot;may be used whenever a
&gt;     subsequent consideration of a URI provides payload content which a
&gt;     strong digest function, such as SHA-1, indicates is identical to a
&gt;     previously recorded version.&quot;
&gt;     http://bibnum.bnf.fr/WARC/WARC_ISO_28500_version1_latestdraft.pdf
&gt;
&gt;     The &quot;WARC-Type: revisit&quot; appears to be flexible enough to allow for
&gt;     different urls. &quot;A &#39;revisit&#39; record describes the revisitation of
&gt;     content already archived&quot;. However it&#39;s not clear that the
&gt;     possibility
&gt;     of different urls was considered.
&gt;
&gt;     So we should discuss and decide what this kind of warc record
&gt;     ought to
&gt;     look like. I&#39;ll offer an initial proposal that it be like the example
&gt;     above, except with a new WARC-Profile
&gt;     &quot;http://netpreserve.org/warc/1.0/revisit/uri-agnostic-identical-payload-digest&quot;.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Setting WARC-Profile to something different from (a &quot;derivative&quot; of) 
&gt; identical-payload-digest does sound like a good start to me.
&gt;

 From a validation point of view a valid URI will do.
At some point the existing profiles should point to a description 
instead of a 404 and so should additional ones. :)

-Nicholas


